#Text=Wikinews interviews Brenton Clutterbuck , candidate for the electorate of Maroochydore at the upcoming Queensland election
#Text=Friday , March 13 , 2009
#Text=Brenton Clutterbuck , Queensland Greens candidate for the electorate of Maroochydore
#Text=Image : Gemma Collins , Brenton Clutterbuck .
#Text=With a Queensland state election coming up in Australia , many minor parties will be looking to hold balance of power and making the major parties listen to what they have to say .
#Text=The Queensland Greens are one of these parties .
#Text=Wikinews reporter Patrick Gillett held an exclusive over-the-phone interview with Greens candidate for the electoral district of Maroochydore , Brenton Clutterbuck .
#Text=Mr. Clutterbuck is a graduate of Sunshine Coast Grammar School and is currently studying Education at the University of the Sunshine Coast .
#Text=Queensland 's unicameral parliament is up for election on March 21 .
#Text=The election campaign will run for a total of 26 days following the issue of the writs by Governor Penelope Wensley .
#Text=Interview
#Text=Some editing of these comments was done by the reporter and may not be exact .
#Text=Why do you want to get into parliament ?
#Text=The main reason is because the electorate is badly underrepresented .
#Text=There are only two other candidates in this electorate , the Labor Party and the LNP .
#Text=Both have poor environmental policy .
#Text=What would the three main policies you are taking into this election be ?
#Text=What we call ‘ Green collar jobs ’ .
#Text=Basically these are environmentally and economically friendly jobs .
#Text=This includes improving transport and installing insulation for homes .
#Text=Managing where the money is going .
#Text=No idealism .
#Text=We would be taking a look at and scrapping a lot of old labor policy such as the Traveston Crossing Dam
#Text=and locally , education .
#Text=Give a lot of support for teachers .
#Text=This applies across primary and secondary schooling as well as at tertiary level .
#Text=How would you address these policies ?
#Text=Basically aim to support as many positive bills as possible .
#Text=If the positive bill is not introduced then you introduce the bill .
#Text=Through cooperation with other members you get things done .
#Text=Whether others listen is another question .
#Text=You should always do what ’s in the best interests of the electorate
#Text=You recently gave comment to the Sunshine Coast Daily about uranium mining in Queensland .
#Text=Does the LNPs position have merit or should they directly invest in renewable energy technology ?
#Text=There is no merit to it , or to Labor 's proposal to invest in uranium .
#Text=We want to have a nuclear free Australia and no nuclear waste .
#Text=Do n’t send overseas where the disposal is up to other countries .
#Text=The 24 hour McDonalds at Mooloolaba in Mr Clutterbucks electorate of Maroochydore
#Text=Image : Patrick Gillett .
#Text=Which renewable energy technology would you prefer to see invested in most ?
#Text=Solar .
#Text=Absolutely solar , it ’s the oldest and most familiar .
#Text=We know a lot about solar .
#Text=We know more about solar than any other technology .
#Text=I ’m getting this from a speech by Ronan Lee
#Text=“ We will build two new solar thermal power stations , one near Townsville and one on the Darling Downs , creating jobs , reducing pollution and making electricity cheaper . ”
#Text=In a recent article I wrote about McDonald ’s appeal against a council decision , you commented that Labor and the LNP [ Liberal National party ] had a long history of being pro big business .
#Text=Would you be willing to introduce policy to the contrary ?
#Text=It ’s not a problem .
#Text=It ’s a problem that big business has influence in those parties .
#Text=It ’s like Springborg with the uranium business donations .
#Text=Big business should not be directing policy
#Text=Should big business back off and respect the community ?
#Text=Should always respect the community desires .
#Text=Community always votes with its feet .
#Text=Where there is a conflict of interest , business should always respect the community .
#Text=As I said before , big business should not be directing policy .
